│               Scheduler                        │
├────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ owner: Owner                                   │
│ task_registry: list[(pet_name, Task)]          │
├────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ refresh()                                      │
│ get_all_tasks()  → list[(str, Task)]           │
│ sort_tasks_by_date() → sorted list             │
│ filter_by_pet(pet_name) → list                 │
│ filter_by_status(completed) → list             │
│ filter_by_type(task_type) → list               │
│ detect_conflicts() → list                      │
│ get_recurring_tasks() → list                   │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
         ▲
         │ receives Owner, reads Owner→Pet→Task
         
         
         
Relationship notes:

Owner → Pet: owner.add_pet(pet) stores Pet in owner.pets. Access via owner.get_pets().
Pet → Task: pet.add_task(task) stores Task in pet.tasks. Tasks live on the Pet, not on the Owner.
Task → Scheduler: Scheduler doesn't own tasks. On creation it calls _build_registry(), which walks Owner → pets → tasks and copies every (pet_name, task) pair into a flat list (task_registry). All scheduling operations run against that flat list